title: For Sale:  Model 1851 Confederate Navy .44 Caliber Brass Frame Revolver
postcontent:
It's a beautiful weapon to say the least. This pistol fires good and packs quite a punch. I've never shot anything through it except wad and ball with pyrodex powder. I use .454 diameter lead balls on a pre-lubed felt wad and topped the chamber with Bore Butter or a tallow-beeswax mix on the ball to prevent fowling in the barrel from burnt powder. The most I put through in a single session was 30 rounds without any malfunctions. That's a lot for a black powder pistol in one sitting! It reloads quickly with the spare cylinder. 
This replica pistol is patterned after the original made with a brass frame to conserve the Southern Confederacy’s limited supplies of steel. Although designated as a Navy pistol, it saw heavy use among Army officers who favored the .44-caliber's  heavy firepower. It features a blued octagonal barrel, plain blued cylinder, tough, attractive walnut grips, and a brass trigger guard. 
I am including everything in the picture: holster, spare cylinder, spare cylinder pouch, nipple wrench, and the rugged black vinyl pistol transport case with plush interior. I've also got the original user's manual that I received with the pistol when I first bought it 10 years ago. It contains detailed loading instructions to prevent any mishaps, and cleaning instructions for maintaining the pistol itself.

postcontent:

There are various models of Smith and Wesson's MP 15. title: For Sale:  Colt 1911 .45  WW1 (1918)  excellent cond.
postcontent:
Up for sale (no trades) 
Colt 1911
serial number dates to 1918
This pistol has been professionally refinished and looks excellent. There doesn't look to be any pitting ever.
This 1911 was from a production run during WW1 when a huge number of pistols were made, so it is not unusual to see them refinished and made into shooters.
There have been a lot of improvements made to this one and it is obvious it was built for range duty.  
I was informed by the previous owner that this pistol was owned by a member of the U.S. Army shooting team, and was tricked out by a nationally known 1911 expert gunsmith who modifys  pistols for Camp Perry competitions.
As you can see, it has Bomar adjustable sights, trigger shoe, dimpled frontstrap & backstrap, and aftermarket grips.
Internally, I was told it has had a trigger job and other internal "refinments" to accurize  it and for reliability. 
I am almost certain it has an aftermarket barrel, I can't see any markings on it.
I have never disassembled this pistol or even fired it. It looks to be in perfect firing condition.
If you contact me I can fill you in on all that I know about it.

               Jim
